Shopping for Answers: The Impact of Geographic
Grocery-Retailer Concentration on Canada’s
Municipal Food Prices
Tayssir Benchoubane
Department of Economics, Carleton University
Abstract. This research examines the relationship between grocery retailer market concentration and
food prices across Canadian municipalities. Using novel concentration measures from OpenStreetMap
data across 18 Canadian cities (2011-2024), this paper provides the ﬁrst comprehensive sub-provincial
analysis of local market structures and food pricing. The ﬁndings indicate that higher grocery retailer
concentration correlates with higher food prices, with this relationship becoming more pronounced above
certain concentration thresholds. Highly concentrated markets exhibit food price indices approximately
3.9 points higher than less concentrated markets, with this gap widening during the COVID-19 pandemic.
Furthermore, an analysis of the 2018 Sobeys-Farm Boy merger reveals that affected markets experienced
food price increases of approximately 3.1 points post-acquisition. These ﬁndings contradict efﬁciency
defenses typically invoked in merger reviews conducted by the Competition Bureau, and suggest market
power signiﬁcantly inﬂuences Canada’s municipal grocery prices.

1 Introduction 2
1 Introduction
Few issues affect Canadians as directly as the price of groceries. With food inﬂation persistently
remaining above overall inﬂation rates in recent years, many consumers have questioned whether
the grocery retail sector is using its market power to increase prices beyond what supply costs would
justify.
1
The Canadian grocery retail landscape is dominated by a small number of large chains. As
of 2023, the “Big Five” retailers—Loblaw Companies Ltd, Sobeys (owned by Empire Company),
Metro Inc, Walmart Canada, and Costco Wholesale—controlled approximately 80% of the food
retail market nationwide
(
Competition Bureau of Canada, 2023)
(
Delibashi, 2023). This high level
of concentration has been developing through decades of consolidation, with notable mergers such
as Loblaw’s acquisition of Shoppers Drug Mart in 2014 and Sobeys’ purchase of Safeway Canada
in 2013 further reducing the number of independent competitors.
2
Discourse regarding the increasing power of grocery retailers intensiﬁed in 2023 when food
inﬂation in Canada reached multi-decade highs, prompting parliamentary inquiries and calls for
enhanced regulatory oversight
(
Alsharif, 2023). Public discontent reached an apex in May 2024,
when a nation-wide boycott of Loblaws was organized to protest increasing grocery prices amidst a
period during which the company saw record high proﬁts (Loblaws, 2024).
Despite the importance of this issue to Canadian consumers and the nation’s economy, empirical
evidence on the relationship between grocery market concentration and food prices remains limited.
Furthermore, due to the data unavailability of food prices sub-provincially, no study of the Canadian
market has offered a granular municipal analysis that considers how subprovincial food price
averages may be affected by geographical concentration, or lack thereof, of grocery retailers.
This research aims to approach this question by constructing novel measures of store density
concentration at the city level and analyzing their relationship with local food price indices. This

that store presence correlates with competitive signiﬁcance in said markets.
I employ and modify both the Herﬁndahl-Hirschman Index (HHI) and the Four-Firm Concentra-
tion Ratio (CR4) as market concentration metrics, calculated from an original database of grocery
store locations compiled through OpenStreetMap (OSM) data across 18 of the largest Canadian
municipalities spanning from 2011-2024. For food prices, I develop yearly city-level food price
indices using a decomposition method that isolates the food component of the Consumer Price
Index while controlling for regional variations in housing costs.
Ultimately, this research ﬁnds that grocery retail concentration is positively associated with
food price levels across Canadian municipalities. Markets with higher concentration consistently
demonstrate higher food prices, with this relationship being particularly pronounced in highly
concentrated markets. I also ﬁnd that the relationship between concentration and prices appears to
be non-linear, with pricing effects becoming more signiﬁcant once concentration exceeds certain
thresholds. Furthermore, the analysis reveals that market concentration ampliﬁed food price inﬂation
during the COVID-19 pandemic, and that consolidation events like the Sobeys-Farm Boy merger
directly contributed to local price increases. These ﬁndings suggest that market power, rather
than efﬁciency gains, is the dominant force shaping the relationship between grocery market
concentration and consumer food prices in Canada.
The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section 2 reviews the existing literature
on market concentration and food prices, highlighting both theoretical perspectives and empirical
evidence from various national contexts. Section 3 details the data collection methodology and
empirical approach, including the construction of the store-count concentration measures and
municipal food price indices. Section 4 provides a preliminary analysis of concentration patterns
across Canadian municipalities and bivariate relationships between concentration and prices. Section
5 presents the main empirical results using multiple econometric speciﬁcations, including ordinary
least squares, ﬁxed-effects, and difference-in-differences models, with particular attention to the
COVID-19 period and a case study of the Sobeys-Farm Boy merger. Section 6 discusses the
2 A Review of the Literature 4
implications of the ﬁndings for competition policy and offers speciﬁc recommendations for reform.
Section 7 acknowledges limitations of the approach and outlines directions for future research.
Finally, Section 8 concludes with an assessment of how the ﬁndings contribute to understanding the
relationship between grocery market concentration and food prices in Canada.
2 A Review of the Literature
The relationship between market concentration and pricing in grocery retailing has been a subject
of signiﬁcant academic inquiry for decades. Since the pioneering work of Stigler
(
1964), numerous
studies have examined how market structure affects consumer prices, with a particular focus on
grocery retailing as an essential sector with substantial economic impact.
Economic theory suggests two competing effects from market concentration. On one hand,
increased concentration may lead to greater market power and higher prices through reduced
competition. In their comprehensive analysis of purchasing power in European food retail, Dobson et
al.
(
2001) argue that concentrated retailers can leverage their position in two directions: downstream
toward consumers through higher retail prices and upstream toward suppliers through depressed
wholesale prices. They identify speciﬁc mechanisms through which this occurs, including listing
charges, slotting allowances, retroactive discounts, and forced application of most-favored-nation
clauses. These practices not only extract greater proﬁts from the supply chain but can ultimately
lead to reduced consumer welfare through higher prices, particularly in markets where few retail
alternatives exist.
On the other hand, some economists, such as Newmark
(
1990) have argued that larger retailers
may achieve economies of scale that could lead to lower prices for consumers. In his ﬁndings,
he contends that consolidation in retail can create efﬁciencies in logistics, distribution networks,
and purchasing power that translate to consumer savings. Newmark particularly emphasizes that
when household income is appropriately controlled for, the relationship between concentration and
higher prices becomes insigniﬁcant. The net effect of these competing forces therefore remains an
empirical question.
2 A Review of the Literature 5
2.1 Empirical Evidence on Market Concentration and Food Prices
Market power in food retailing is particularly important as McCorriston
(
2002) notes that food
markets in Europe and elsewhere are typically oligopolistic. The empirical literature examining
the relationship between market concentration and food prices presents somewhat mixed results,
though the majority of studies indicate a positive relationship. As Yu and Connor
(
2002) note in
their re-examination of Newmark’s
(
1990) study; of the dozen or so published studies on grocery
retailing, only two found no positive and statistically signiﬁcant relationship between concentration
and price. Yu and Connor
(
2002) also demonstrated that when proper concentration measures are
used, a positive relationship between concentration and prices emerges consistently. Their analysis
showed that depending on the concentration measure, prices in the most concentrated markets were
approximately 3.3% to 8.4% higher than in the least concentrated markets. Marion et al.
(
1979),
Lamm
(
1981), and Cotterill
(
1986) all found similar evidence: increased concentration in grocery
retailing was associated with higher prices.
Geographic studies also seem to support these ﬁndings. Aalto-Set
¨
al
¨
a
(
2002) examined the
Finnish grocery retail industry and found that the main factor affecting market power was the size
of the retail ﬁrm, with larger-share grocery retailers carrying higher markups in both local and
national markets. The author concluded that “the main purpose of large grocery retail mergers is
to gain market power not efﬁciency.”
ˇ
Spi
ˇ
cka (2016) also studied European grocery markets and
found that most had structures of asymmetric oligopoly, where three or four companies dominate.
Interestingly, his study found no strong direct relationship between market power and proﬁtability
of grocery retailers.
An important distinction found in the literature is between national and local concentration
measures.
C¸
akır et al. (2020) emphasize that food retailing is inherently local and that concentration
should be measured at the appropriate geographic level. Their study found that local HHI at the
county level was approximately 16 percentage points higher than national HHI, with rural markets
showing substantially higher concentration (24% HHI) compared to metropolitan markets (13%
2 A Review of the Literature 6
HHI). This aligns with ﬁndings from Rossi-Hansberg, Sarte, and Trachter
(
2018) who documented
diverging trends in national and local concentration across various industries. Their work suggests
that analyzing only national concentration can mask important competitive dynamics occurring at
the local level. These ﬁndings further cement the rationale behind introducing a more localized
analysis to explore the Canadian grocery sector.
2.2 The Canadian Context
Research speciﬁc to the Canadian grocery market is relatively limited compared to studies on the
U.S. market. The Competition Bureau of Canada
(
2023) report “Competition in Canada from 2000
to 2020” documents that concentration rose in the most concentrated industries across the Canadian
economy during the two decades. The report found that the number of industries with an HHI
greater than 2,500 rose from 19 in 2005 to 27 in 2018, indicating a broad trend toward increased
concentration. However, due to privacy limitations imposed by Statistics Canada, the report falls
short of identifying which speciﬁc industries saw the greatest increase in concentration relative to
others. The Competition Bureau’s analysis further reveals that “rank stability” increased across
industries, meaning that the same ﬁrms remained at the top of their industries over time, facing less
challenge from competitors. The report also documents that markups and proﬁts rose, especially in
industries that were already the most proﬁtable.
Bawania and Larkin
(
2019) examined whether Canadian industries were becoming more con-
centrated and found evidence of increasing concentration in the retail sector. However, their study
was broader in scope and did not focus speciﬁcally on grocery retailing. A more recent report from
HEC Montr
´
eal
(
2022) suggests that Canada’s competition policy may have played a key role in
slowing productivity and economic growth in Canada, highlighting potential issues with the current
regulatory approach to market concentration. The report critiques Canada’s permissive merger
review process and argues that the Competition Act’s efﬁciency defense
(
Competition Act (R.S.C.,
1985, c. C-34), 2024), which allows mergers that may substantially lessen competition if they
generate sufﬁcient efﬁciencies, has contributed to increased concentration across multiple sectors of
3 Data and Methods 7
the Canadian economy.
There is a notable gap in the Canadian literature regarding the measurement of local grocery
market concentration using store-level geographic data. Unlike the United States, where the
Federal Trade Commission and academic researchers have conducted numerous studies examining
local concentration using store counts and locations
(C¸
akır, Kong, Cho, & Stevens, 2020), no
comprehensive study has applied similar methodologies to Canadian grocery markets despite its
highly concentrated nature.
3 Data and Methods
This research required assembling a comprehensive dataset that could capture both the geographic
distribution of grocery retailers across Canadian municipalities and the temporal evolution of both
market concentration and food prices from 2011 to 2024. Therefore, two critical components were
necessary for the analysis: a historical database of grocery store locations, and municipal-level food
price indices.
For the spatial component, I leveraged OpenStreetMap (OSM), a collaborative mapping platform
that functions as a free, editable geographic database of the world. Unlike proprietary mapping
services such as Google Maps, which primarily provides cross-sectional data representing the
current state of locations, OSM maintains historical snapshots that allow researchers to query how
the geographic landscape has changed over time.
For the price component, I faced the challenge that Statistics Canada does not directly publish
food price indices at the municipal level, with data primarily available at the provincial scale. To
overcome this limitation, I developed a decomposition method using existing Consumer Price Index
(CPI) data. This approach extracts the food-speciﬁc component from municipal all-items CPIs by
accounting for the differential impacts of shelter costs and other geographically variable expenses.
The resulting database allowed for a more granular analysis than previously possible, allowing
for the ﬁrst sub-provincial examination of how local grocery market structures affect food pricing
outcomes across Canadian cities.
3 Data and Methods 8
3.1 Estimating Store-Count Concentration Measures
The reviewed literature highlights several methodological considerations relevant to the study. First,
the deﬁnition of the relevant market matters signiﬁcantly. Yu and Connor
(
2002) emphasize that
failing to exclude non-competing retailers from concentration measures can lead to erroneous
conclusions. With this consideration in mind, I carefully deﬁne the relevant market to include only
supermarkets and grocery stores, excluding convenience stores and other non-competing retail
formats. Second, as noted by Set
¨
al
¨
a
(
2002), the spatial dimension of competition is particularly
important in grocery retailing as consumers typically shop within a limited geographic range due to
transportation costs and time constraints; the reﬁnement of accurate geographic boundaries was
therefore critical.
There exists no publicly available database of grocery chains across Canada. To construct the
dataset of grocery store locations, I developed a custom data collection code utilizing Python and
the Overpass API, which provides access to OSM data.
3
The data collection process involved
querying yearly snapshots of OSM custom polygons from 2011 to 2024 across 18 Canadian mu-
nicipal areas. The cities included in the study were: St. John’s (Newfoundland and Labrador),
Charlottetown and Summerside (Prince Edward Island), Halifax (Nova Scotia), Montreal (Quebec),
Saint John (New Brunswick), Quebec City (Quebec), Thunder Bay (Ontario), Winnipeg (Mani-
toba), Regina (Saskatchewan), Ottawa-Gatineau, Ontario part (Ontario/Quebec), Toronto (Ontario),
Saskatoon (Saskatchewan), Calgary (Alberta), Victoria (British Columbia), Yellowknife (Northwest
Territories), Whitehorse (Yukon), Vancouver (British Columbia), and Edmonton (Alberta).
To ensure accurate geographic representation of each municipality, I deﬁned the precise ge-
ographic boundaries of the municipal areas using polygon coordinates extracted from Statistics
Canada’s
(
2021) Census Cartographic Boundary Files (CBF). Each polygon consists of a series of
latitude and longitude coordinates that collectively outline the ofﬁcial administrative boundaries
of the municipalities under study. This approach enabled the analysis to reﬂect the true market

Given the fragmented nature of grocery store branding, where multiple store banners often
belong to the same parent company, the next step was to implement a data cleaning process to
accurately identify grocery chain ownership; this in turn would allow for an accurate calculation
of concentration measures. First, I standardized all store names and operator ﬁelds by converting
them to uppercase and removing special characters, accented letters, and punctuation. This step was
important for consistent pattern matching across entries with varying name formats - a limitation of
the crowd-sourced nature of OSM. I then implemented a ﬁrm identiﬁcation code using partial string
matching to assign each store to its parent company. For instance, stores operating as Maxi, No
Frills, and Superstore were all identiﬁed as belonging to the Loblaws group. Similarly, stores under
banners like Foodland, IGA or Freshco, were assigned to the Sobey’s group. This step covered a
long list of subsidiaries as listed in Figure 1 of the Competition Bureau’s report
(
2023). I applied
similar classiﬁcations for other major retail groups including Metro, Jim Pattison Group, Walmart,
and Costco. I also considered Farm Boy and Longo’s locations as independent prior to their mergers
with Sobey’s in 2018 and 2021 respectively.

how HHI and CR4 are traditionally calculated. Additionally, the DCR adjustment introduces
another layer of estimation that might affect how concentration measures compare to standard
thresholds. What matters most for the purposes of this paper is the relative comparison
between more and less concentrated markets within the Canadian sample; therefore, I create a
90th percentile treshold to distingish highly concentrated markets in the municipal Canadian
context as seen in Table 2. It should also be noted that the treshholds for both indices are
theoretically sound as per Naldi and Flamini’s (2014) classiﬁcation.

5 Empirical Analysis
The preliminary exploration established a positive bivariate relationship between grocery market
concentration and food prices across Canadian municipalities. However, to identify causal rela-
tionships and control for potential confounding factors, more rigorous econometric techniques are
required. This section presents a systematic analysis of how grocery retail concentration affects con-
sumer food prices, examining both the magnitude and statistical signiﬁcance of these relationships
under various model speciﬁcations.

compared to other controls.

6 Summary of Key Findings
This research has examined the relationship between grocery market concentration and food prices
across Canadian municipalities using multiple methodological approaches. By constructing novel
measures of store-based concentration at the municipal level and applying various econometric
techniques, I have found compelling evidence that market structure signiﬁcantly inﬂuences consumer
food prices, particularly during periods of economic disruption.
First, store-count grocery retail concentration is seemingly positively associated with food price
levels. In the cross-sectional analysis using the HHI, markets in the top decile of concentration
experience food price indices approximately 6.4 points higher than less concentrated markets,
representing a premium of roughly 4.3% relative to the average Food CPI of 149.5. This ﬁnding
aligns with previous empirical research (Marion et al., 1979; Lamm, 1981; Cotterill, 1986; Yu and
Connor, 2002), and suggests that market power in Canadian grocery retailing translates into higher
consumer prices.
The ﬁndings also seem to point towards the idea that the relationship between retailer concen-
tration and food prices is non-linear. In the ﬁxed-effects models, which control for unobserved
time-invariant city characteristics, continuous measures of concentration show positive but often
statistically insigniﬁcant relationships with food prices. However, binary indicators for high con-
centration consistently demonstrate stronger and statistically signiﬁcant effects. Speciﬁcally, when
6 Summary of Key Findings 48
municipalities cross into the top decile of concentration, food prices increase by approximately 3.9
points for HHI and 3.7 points for CR4. This suggests a threshold effect where market concentration
must reach a certain level before pricing power becomes pronounced.
A difference-in-differences analysis of the COVID-19 period was then conducted. The exper-
iment demonstrated that retailer concentration ampliﬁed food price inﬂation during the period’s
supply chain disruptions. Markets with high HHI experienced inﬂation rates approximately 2.5
percentage points higher than less concentrated markets, representing nearly 50% of the average
inﬂation increase during this period. This indicates that concentrated retail markets were less
resilient to supply chain disruptions and/or retailers in these markets exploited their market presence
during the crisis period.
Finally, the case study of the 2018 Sobeys-Farm Boy merger provides evidence of the direct
impact that Empire Company’s consolidation had on consumer prices. Markets with Farm Boy
presence experienced food price increases of approximately 3.1 points higher than control markets
following the merger. Notably, the effect peaked one year after acquisition, with a coefﬁcient of
4.8, before gradually attenuating, which could mean that consolidated entities implement price
adjustments after integration is complete rather than immediately following acquisition.
Across all speciﬁcations, the HHI measure consistently demonstrated stronger and more sta-
tistically signiﬁcant relationships with food prices compared to the CR4 measure. This suggests
that the overall distribution of market shares among all competitors, rather than just the combined
market power of the largest ﬁrms, plays a more important role in determining pricing outcomes in
grocery retail markets.
These ﬁndings contradict the efﬁciency defense often invoked in merger reviews, which suggests
that consolidation generates economies of scale that beneﬁt consumers through lower prices. Instead,
the empirical evidence aligns with the market power hypothesis, wherein concentration enables
retailers to exercise pricing power to the detriment of consumers, with these effects becoming
particularly pronounced during economic disruptions.
7 Competition Policy Implications and Recommendations 49
7 Competition Policy Implications and Recommendations
This paper’s ﬁndings on the relationship between market concentration and food prices in Canadian
municipalities have implications for competition policy. Three aspects merit particular attention
in light of the results: merger review standards, abuse of dominance provisions, and the efﬁciency
defense framework under Canada’s Competition Act (R.S.C., 1985, c. C-34).
7.1 Merger Review and Concentration Thresholds
The analysis of the Sobeys-Farm Boy merger demonstrates that even acquisitions of regional chains
by national retailers can produce measurable increases in consumer prices. The magnitude of the
price effect suggests that Canada’s current merger review process may not adequately predict or
prevent consumer harm from retail consolidation. The Competition Bureau’s historically permissive
approach to grocery retail mergers appears inconsistent with the empirical evidence of post-merger
price effects (Nixon, 2024).
Unlike jurisdictions that employ more stringent concentration thresholds, Canada’s Competition
Bureau generally will not challenge mergers unless they produce market shares exceeding 35% for
unilateral effects or CR4 exceeding 65% for coordinated effects. Notably, the Bureau explicitly
states it “does not use HHI levels to delineate any safe harbour threshold,”
(
Competition Bureau of
Canada, 2024). Given the ﬁnding that crossing into high concentration thresholds is associated with
signiﬁcant price increases, I recommend:
•
Adopting explicit HHI-based thresholds where mergers resulting in markets with HHI above
1,800 and increasing HHI by more than 100 points should be presumptively illegal
•
Implementing stricter thresholds for rural and small non-metropolitan markets, where the
study shows concentration levels are typically higher
•
Requiring speciﬁc local market concentration analysis for all grocery retail mergers, regardless
of national concentration effects
7 Competition Policy Implications and Recommendations 50
• Mandating that the Competition Bureau consider evidence of price effects from comparable
past mergers when evaluating likely competitive effects
7.2 Addressing Market Power and Abuse of Dominance
The Competition Act’s abuse of dominance provisions (sections 78 and 79) may be insufﬁciently
calibrated to address market power concerns in grocery retailing. Canada’s high legal thresholds for
proving abuse of dominance - requiring demonstration that conduct substantially lessens competition
- may prevent effective intervention when concentration gradually increases through multiple
transactions over time. The ﬁnding that concentration effects were most pronounced during supply
chain disruptions, as seen during COVID-19, suggests that dominance concerns are particularly
acute during economic crises, when consumers are most vulnerable to price exploitation. To address
these concerns, I recommend:
•
Creating a sliding scale of notiﬁcation and review thresholds based on pre-existing local
market concentration, with lower thresholds for already concentrated markets
•
Establishing a rebuttable presumption of anti-competitive effects when prices rise following a
merger in concentrated markets
•
Implementing mandatory post-merger price monitoring for approved grocery retail mergers
for a period of at least three years
7.3 Reforming the Efﬁciency Defense
Finally, this research directly challenges the Competition Act’s efﬁciency defense (section 96),
which allows mergers that lessen competition substantially if they generate sufﬁcient efﬁciencies.
This defense effectively prioritizes producer welfare over consumer welfare by permitting mergers
that increase prices if the merged entity realizes sufﬁcient cost savings. The Supreme Court
of Canada’s decision in Tervita Corp. v. Canada
(
2015) further strengthened this approach by
7 Competition Policy Implications and Recommendations 51
establishing a relatively low threshold for proving efﬁciency gains.
19
This paper’s empirical results ﬁnd no evidence that higher concentration is associated with lower
marginal costs that might offset higher markup ratios. The consistent positive relationship between
concentration and prices across the models suggests that any efﬁciency gains from consolidation
in Canadian grocery retailing are not being passed on to consumers in the form of lower prices.
This aligns with research from HEC Montr
´
eal suggesting that Canada’s efﬁciency defense has
contributed to increased concentration without corresponding productivity beneﬁts
(
HEC Montr
´
eal,
2022). It is therefore recommended that the defense be amended in that:
•
Reforming section 96(1) to require that efﬁciencies “beneﬁt consumers through lower prices,
improved quality, or increased innovation” rather than merely requiring that they “offset”
anti-competitive effects
•
Explicitly incorporating a “consumer pass-through” requirement, whereby efﬁciency claims
are only cognizable if a reasonable portion of the claimed efﬁciencies would likely be passed
on to Canadian consumers
• Addressing the information asymmetry highlighted in the Tervita decision by enhancing the
Bureau’s investigative powers and analytical capabilities for assessing efﬁciency claims
These reforms would help prevent the further consolidation of grocery retail markets and the
associated consumer harm through higher prices that this paper has identiﬁed, while still protecting
legitimate efﬁciencies that beneﬁt consumers. By requiring consumer beneﬁts and implementing
stricter concentration thresholds, these amendments would better balance the dual goals of economic
efﬁciency and consumer welfare in Canadian competition policy.
19
In Tervita, the Supreme Court established that when the Competition Bureau fails to properly quantify anti-
competitive effects, even minimal efﬁciencies can justify an anti-competitive merger. Justice Rothstein’s majority
opinion emphasized that “there is no basis to conclude that something more than marginal efﬁciency gains are required”
to satisfy the efﬁciencies defense.
8 Limitations and Further Research 52
8 Limitations and Further Research
8.1 Data Limitations
A signiﬁcant limitation of our research concerns the measurement of market concentration. the
store-count approach using OSM data, while innovative, differs from traditional concentration
metrics based on sales data. Store counts may not perfectly correlate with market share, as stores
vary substantially in size and sales volume. Additionally, the OSM database suffers from temporal
inconsistency, with more comprehensive coverage in recent years compared to earlier periods in the
sample. Although I implemented density correction ratios to address this imbalance, this remains
an imperfect solution that may introduce measurement error.
Geographic market deﬁnition presents another challenge. By deﬁning markets at the municipal
level, I may not perfectly capture the relevant competitive landscape. Consumers may shop across
municipal boundaries, particularly in metropolitan areas with multiple adjacent municipalities.
Future research could employ more granular approaches using an isochrone analysis to better
approximate actual shopping patterns.
The approach to estimating municipal food price indices also has limitations. Since Statistics
Canada does not report city-level food CPIs directly, I employed a decomposition method to isolate
food-speciﬁc components from the overall CPI. While theoretically sound, the method assumes
provincial basket weights apply uniformly across municipalities, potentially overlooking important
local consumption patterns and price dynamics. Future research could beneﬁt from developing or
accessing more direct measures of local food prices, potentially through retailer scanner data or
targeted price surveys.
8.2 Methodological Limitations
In terms of the competitive dynamics assumptions, the market power exercised by retailers depends
not only on horizontal competition at the retail level but also on their bargaining power in relation to
8 Limitations and Further Research 53
suppliers. the concentration measures do not directly account for vertical market power dynamics.
Future research could incorporate measures of buyer concentration and supplier concentration to
develop a more comprehensive understanding of market power throughout the food supply chain.
Additionally, the focus on retail-level concentration may obscure the important role of upstream
concentration in the food supply chain. The observed price effects might not be solely attributable
to grocery retailer concentration but could reﬂect market power exercised by food manufacturers,
processors, or agricultural producers.
It should also be noted that the analysis treats all grocery items as a homogeneous category.
However, as suggested by , the relationship between concentration and prices may vary across
different product categories. For instance, the effect might be stronger for dry grocery products
compared to fresh and chilled foods. Future research could disaggregate price effects by product
category to provide more nuanced insights. Additionally, the competitive dynamics may differ
between national brand products and private label offerings, which the current analysis does not
distinguish.
Finally, the ﬁxed effects and difference-in-differences speciﬁcations help address unobserved
heterogeneity, but cannot fully account for time-varying confounding factors that might correlate
with both market concentration and food prices. For example, changes in local economic conditions,
retailer quality improvements, or demographic shifts could inﬂuence both market structure and
pricing behavior in ways the models cannot fully capture.
8.3 Directions for Further Research
The study reveals several avenues for future research that would address key limitations and extend
the understanding of the relationship between grocery market concentration and food prices:
1.
Structural Models of the Food Supply Chain: To address limitations in attributing price
effects solely to retail concentration, future research should develop structural econometric
models that simultaneously account for market power at multiple stages of the food supply
8 Limitations and Further Research 54
chain.
20
These models could decompose observed price effects into components attributable
to retail concentration, manufacturer concentration, and primary producer concentration,
providing a more nuanced understanding of market power throughout the food system.
2.
Crisis-Period Market Power Dynamics: The ﬁnding that concentration ampliﬁed food
price inﬂation during COVID-19 warrants dedicated research into how market power operates
during economic disruptions. Future studies could leverage natural experiments created
by supply chain shocks to identify whether price increases in concentrated markets during
crises reﬂect genuine cost pass-through or opportunistic exploitation of market power.
21
This research would have signiﬁcant implications for competition policy during economic
emergencies.
3.
Merger Effects and Market Adjustment: Building on the Sobeys-Farm Boy case study,
further research should examine the temporal dynamics of post-merger price adjustments.
the ﬁnding that price effects peaked one year post-merger before partially attenuating raises
important questions about market adjustment mechanisms. Research employing longer time
series and examining multiple merger events could identify patterns in how consolidation
effects evolve over time and what factors inﬂuence their persistence.
22
4. Heterogeneous Effects Across Product Categories and Markets: More granular analysis
of how concentration affects prices across different product categories and market types would
provide insights into the mechanisms through which market power operates.

This could
help distinguish between retailer market power effects and upstream manufacturer power,
while also identifying which consumer segments are most vulnerable to concentration-related

The divergent COVID-19 experiences across different product categories within grocery stores (e.g., shelf-stable
vs. fresh foods) could provide valuable variation for identiﬁcation of these effects.
22
This could include examining how entry by new competitors, consumer substitution patterns, or public scrutiny
affects post-merger pricing behavior.

with high brand loyalty or limited substitution options.

rural markets, where the data suggests concentration patterns differ substantially.
5.
Non-Price Effects and Total Welfare Analysis: While the focus on price effects provides
important insights, a comprehensive evaluation of concentration’s impact should include
non-price outcomes such as product quality, variety, innovation, and food waste.

Structural
demand estimation could help quantify consumer welfare effects beyond price, providing a
more complete picture of how concentration affects overall market performance in grocery
retailing.
These research directions would contribute to both the academic literature on industrial organization
and to evidence-based competition policy development potentially leading to more targeted and
effective regulatory approaches than the ones presented in this research.
9 Concluding Remarks
This study provides new evidence on the relationship between grocery market concentration and
food prices in Canadian municipalities. Through a novel data collection methodology complemented
with a variety of econometric analyses, several important ﬁndings were established.
Canadian grocery markets exhibit substantial variation in concentration levels across municipal-
ities, with particularly high concentration in Atlantic Canada and more moderate levels in major
metropolitan areas. The “Big Five” retailers - Loblaw, Sobeys, Metro, Walmart, and Costco -
dominate the landscape, collectively controlling nearly 60% of store presence in the sample, with
the top three Canadian-owned chains alone accounting for 49% of stores.
This paper presented evidence that grocery retailer concentration is meaningfully associated with
higher food prices, but this relationship manifests most strongly at high concentration thresholds.
A difference-in-differences analys revealed that market power dynamics seemingly intensiﬁed
during the COVID-19 economic shock, with highly concentrated markets experienced signiﬁcantly
24
Food deserts - geographic areas with limited access to affordable and nutritious food - represent a particularly
important non-price outcome that may be inﬂuenced by market concentration.
9 Concluding Remarks 56
higher inﬂation rates. Finally, a case study of the Sobeys-Farm Boy merger offered evidence of
merger-speciﬁc effects on local prices. Markets affected by this acquisition experienced food price
increases following the merger, with effects peaking one year post-acquisition.
These ﬁndings contradict the efﬁciency defense often invoked in merger reviews, which suggests
that consolidation generates economies of scale that beneﬁt consumers through lower prices. Instead,
this research aligns with the market power hypothesis, wherein concentration enables retailers to
exercise pricing power to the detriment of consumers. The Competition Bureau of Canada may
need to reassess its merger review policies in the grocery sector, particularly the “efﬁciency defense”
that has permitted substantial consolidation. Regulatory authorities might also consider more
stringent merger enforcement, especially in markets already exhibiting high concentration levels.
Additionally, targeted monitoring of pricing practices during economic shocks may be warranted to
prevent the exploitation of market power during periods of consumer vulnerability.
As food inﬂation remains a pressing concern for Canadian households, understanding the
structural market factors that contribute to price increases becomes increasingly important. This
research suggests that promoting more competitive grocery retail markets could be an effective
strategy for moderating food price inﬂation and improving consumer welfare. The challenge for
policymakers lies in balancing the legitimate scale efﬁciencies of modern food retailing with the
competitive dynamics necessary to ensure fair pricing for Canadian consumers.
The Canadian grocery landscape stands at a crossroads. Further concentration may promise
operational efﬁciencies and international competitiveness for retailers, but the evidence suggests
these beneﬁts may not be shared with consumers. As the industry continues to evolve, maintaining
robust competition will be essential to ensuring food affordability and accessibility for all Canadians.
